Library\n+\n+Cockpit is a **voice-first** cross-platform spatial workspace library for managing floating windows in AR/2D environments. Designed for deep integration with VoiceOS accessibility service.\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Module Info\n+\n+| Property | Value |\n+|----------|-------|\n+| Type | Package (KMP Library) |\n+| Platforms | Android, iOS, Desktop, Web |\n+| Path | `Common/Cockpit` |\n+| Namespace | `com.avanues.cockpit` |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Core Concept\n+\n+**Voice-first** spatial workspace system enabling multi-window layouts similar to Apple Vision Pro but with unique Cockpit identity. Manages floating windows containing apps, tools, dashboards, and remote desktops.\n+\n+**CRITICAL**: Voice is the primary interaction method. All features MUST be fully operable via voice commands through VoiceOS integration.\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Voice-First Design\n+\n+| Principle | Requirement |\n+|-----------|-------------|\n+| Voice Primary | Every action accessible via voice command |\n+| VoiceOS Integration | Deep integration with VoiceOS accessibility service |\n+| Natural Language | Support conversational commands, not just keywords |\n+| Voice Feedback | Audio confirmation for all actions |\n+| Hands-Free Operation | Complete workflow possible without touch/mouse |\n+| Multi-Modal Fallback | Touch/gaze/keyboard as secondary options |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## VoiceOS Integration\n+\n+### Core Integration Points\n+\n+| Component | VoiceOS Role |\n+|-----------|--------------|\n+| Window Management | \"Open browser\", \"Close calculator\", \"Focus email\" |\n+| Layout Control | \"Switch to theater mode\", \"Arrange in arc\" |\n+| Navigation | \"Next window\", \"Previous workspace\", \"Go to settings\" |\n+| Workspace Actions | \"Save workspace as work setup\", \"Load evening layout\" |\n+| Window Manipulation | \"Move email left\", \"Make browser bigger\", \"Pin this window\" |\n+| Content Interaction | Read window contents, interact with apps via voice |\n+\n+### VoiceOS Communication Protocol\n+\n+```kotlin\n+interface VoiceOSBridge {\n+    // Cockpit → VoiceOS\n+    suspend fun requestVoiceInput(): VoiceCommand\n+    suspend fun announceAction(action: String)\n+    suspend fun requestAccessibilityInfo(windowId: String): AccessibilityNode\n+\n+    // VoiceOS → Cockpit\n+    fun onVoiceCommand(command: VoiceCommand)\n+    fun onAccessibilityEvent(event: AccessibilityEvent)\n+    fun onGazeTarget(target: GazeTarget)\n+}\n+```\n+\n+### Accessibility Service Integration\n+\n+| Feature | Implementation |\n+|---------|----------------|\n+| Window Content Access | VoiceOS reads window contents via accessibility nodes |\n+| App Control | VoiceOS controls apps within windows (click buttons, fill forms) |\n+| Navigation Context | VoiceOS announces current window, layout, focus state |\n+| Spatial Audio Cues | Audio feedback for window positions in 3D space |\n+| Voice Shortcuts | Custom voice macros for common workspace operations |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Window Model\n+\n+```kotlin\n+data class AppWindow(\n+    val id: String,\n+    val title: String,\n+    val type: WindowType,\n+    val sourceId: String,\n+    val position: Vector3D,\n+    val rotation: Quaternion,\n+    val widthMeters: Float,\n+    val heightMeters: Float,\n+    val zLayer: Int,\n+    val pinned: Boolean,\n+    val visible: Boolean,\n+\n+    // Voice-first additions\n+    val voiceName: String,              // How VoiceOS refers to this window\n+    val voiceDescription: String,       // Announced when window gains focus\n+    val voiceShortcuts: List<String>,   // Custom voice commands for this window\n+    val spatialAudioEnabled: Boolean    // 3D audio positioning for voice feedback\n+)\n+\n+enum class WindowType {\n+    ANDROID_APP,\n+    WEB_APP,\n+    REMOTE_DESKTOP,\n+    WIDGET\n+}\n+```\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Layout Presets\n+\n+| Preset | Description | Voice Command |\n+|--------|-------------|---------------|\n+| LINEAR_HORIZONTAL | 5-6 windows in horizontal array (DEFAULT) | \"Linear mode\" |\n+| ARC_3_FRONT | Three windows in curved arc | \"Arc mode\" |\n+| GRID_2x2 | Four evenly sized windows | \"Grid mode\" |\n+| STACK_CENTER | One main + stacked background | \"Stack mode\" |\n+| THEATER | Large cinema window + side tools | \"Theater mode\" |\n+\n+**Default**: LINEAR_HORIZONTAL (macOS/Vision Pro style)\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Visual Identity\n+\n+### Window Styles (User-Configurable via Voice)\n+\n+| Element | Minimal Style (DEFAULT) | Glass Style | Voice Command |\n+|---------|-------------------------|-------------|---------------|\n+| Window Borders | Very subtle or none | Thin dark-glass with soft glow | \"Minimal borders\" / \"Glass borders\" |\n+| Background | Neutral gradient, soft lighting | Same | - |\n+| Shadows | Soft drop shadows | Enhanced with glow | - |\n+| Perspective | Slight 3D tilt | Slight 3D tilt | - |\n+\n+### Colors & Effects\n+\n+| Element | Style |\n+|---------|-------|\n+| Accent Colors | Blue (comm), Orange (data), Green (utils) |\n+| Curvature | Horizontal curve on large windows (optional) |\n+| Lighting | Soft ambient lighting, neutral gradient background |\n+\n+### Control UI (Hybrid Approach)\n+\n+| Component | Location | Purpose | Voice Command |\n+|-----------|----------|---------|---------------|\n+| **Window Dock** | Bottom center | Dot indicators for windows, active highlight | \"Show dock\" / \"Hide dock\" |\n+| **Control Rail** | Top or side (floating) | Home, Workspace, Layout, Voice, Settings | \"Show controls\" / \"Hide controls\" |\n+| **Utility Belt** | Bottom corners | Music, timers, battery, notifications | \"Show utilities\" |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Voice Command Examples\n+\n+### Window Management\n+| Command | Action |\n+|---------|--------|\n+| \"Open Gmail\" | Opens Gmail in new window |\n+| \"Close browser\" | Closes browser window |\n+| \"Focus calculator\" | Brings calculator to front |\n+| \"Show all windows\" | Overview mode with all windows |\n+| \"Hide music player\" | Sets window invisible |\n+\n+### Layout & Positioning\n+| Command | Action |\n+|---------|--------|\n+| \"Linear mode\" | Switches to LINEAR_HORIZONTAL (default) |\n+| \"Arc mode\" | Switches to ARC_3_FRONT layout |\n+| \"Grid mode\" | Switches to GRID_2x2 layout |\n+| \"Stack mode\" | Switches to STACK_CENTER layout |\n+| \"Theater mode\" | Switches to THEATER layout |\n+| \"Move email to the right\" | Repositions window spatially |\n+| \"Make browser bigger\" | Increases window dimensions |\n+| \"Pin this window\" | Pins current focused window |\n+\n+### Visual Customization\n+| Command | Action |\n+|---------|--------|\n+| \"Minimal borders\" | Switches to minimal window border style |\n+| \"Glass borders\" | Switches to dark-glass border style with glow |\n+| \"Show dock\" / \"Hide dock\" | Toggles window dock visibility |\n+| \"Show controls\" / \"Hide controls\" | Toggles Control Rail visibility |\n+| \"Show utilities\" | Displays Utility Belt |\n+\n+### Workspace Management\n+| Command | Action |\n+|---------|--------|\n+| \"Save workspace as morning routine\" | Saves current layout with name |\n+| \"Load work setup\" | Restores saved workspace |\n+| \"Next workspace\" | Cycles to next workspace |\n+| \"Delete this workspace\" | Removes current workspace |\n+\n+### Content Interaction (via VoiceOS)\n+| Command | Action |\n+|---------|--------|\n+| \"Read this window\" | VoiceOS reads window contents |\n+| \"Click sign in button\" | VoiceOS clicks button in focused window |\n+| \"Scroll down\" | VoiceOS scrolls current window |\n+| \"What's in the email window?\" | VoiceOS describes window content |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Interaction Rules\n+\n+| Action | Behavior |\n+|--------|----------|\n+| **Voice (Primary)** | All operations via natural language commands |\n+| Focus | Window enlarges, full opacity, spatial audio cue |\n+| Background | Windows shrink, reduced opacity |\n+| Move/Resize | Voice primary, gesture/controller fallback |\n+| Voice Feedback | Audio confirmation with spatial positioning |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Platform Support\n+\n+| Platform | Rendering | Input | VoiceOS Integration |\n+|----------|-----------|-------|---------------------|\n+| Android | ARCore + Compose | Voice (PRIMARY), Touch, Gaze | Full accessibility service |\n+| iOS | ARKit + SwiftUI | Voice (PRIMARY), Touch, Eye Tracking | VoiceOver integration |\n+| Desktop | OpenGL/Vulkan | Voice (PRIMARY), Mouse, Keyboard | System voice commands |\n+| Web | WebXR + Canvas | Voice (PRIMARY), Mouse, Keyboard | Web Speech API |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Design Principles\n+\n+| Principle | Implementation |\n+|-----------|----------------|\n+| **Voice-First** | Voice is primary input, all features voice-accessible |\n+| **VoiceOS Native** | Deep integration with VoiceOS accessibility service |\n+| Platform Agnostic | Core logic in commonMain |\n+| Extensible | Plugin architecture for custom windows |\n+| Performance | 60fps minimum, efficient rendering |\n+| | Every action accessible via voice command |\n+| VoiceOS Integration | Deep integration with VoiceOS accessibility service |\n+| Natural Language | Support conversational commands, not just keywords |\n+| Voice Feedback | Audio confirmation for all actions |\n+| Hands-Free Operation | Complete workflow possible without touch/mouse |\n+| Multi-Modal Fallback | Touch/gaze/keyboard as secondary options |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## VoiceOS Integration\n+\n+### Core Integration Points\n+\n+| Component | VoiceOS Role |\n+|-----------|--------------|\n+| Window Management | \"Open browser\", \"Close calculator\", \"Focus email\" |\n+| Layout Control | \"Switch to theater mode\", \"Arrange in arc\" |\n+| Navigation | \"Next window\", \"Previous workspace\", \"Go to settings\" |\n+| Workspace Actions | \"Save workspace as work setup\", \"Load evening layout\" |\n+| Window Manipulation | \"Move email left\", \"Make browser bigger\", \"Pin this window\" |\n+| Content Interaction | Read window contents, interact with apps via voice |\n+\n+### VoiceOS Communication Protocol\n+\n+```kotlin\n+interface VoiceOSBridge {\n+    // Cockpit → VoiceOS\n+    suspend fun requestVoiceInput(): (click buttons, fill forms) |\n+| Navigation Context | VoiceOS announces current window, layout, focus state |\n+| Spatial Audio Cues | Audio feedback for window positions in 3D space |\n+| Voice Shortcuts | Custom voice macros for common workspace operations |\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Window Model\n+\n+```kotlin\n+data class AppWindow(\n+    val id: String,\n+    val title: String,\n+    val type: // Announced when window gains focus\n+    val voiceShortcuts: List<String>,   // Custom voice commands for this window\n+    val spatialAudioEnabled: Boolean    // 3D audio positioning for voice |\n+\n+**Default**: LINEAR_HORIZONTAL (macOS/Vision Pro style)\n+\n+---\n+\n+## Visual Identity\n+\n+### Window Styles (User-Configurable via Voice)\n+\n+| Element | Minimal Style (DEFAULT) | Glass How to interpret their output if not obvious?_\n\n**Git merge with automatic conflict resolution:**\n1. `rm -f .git/index.lock` - Remove stale lock file (if needed)\n2. `git merge {branch} -X theirs --no-edit` - Merge accepting all incoming changes\n3. Strategy `-X theirs`: Automatically resolve conflicts by accepting changes from branch being merged\n4. `--no-edit`: Skip commit message editor, use default merge message\n5. Output: Shows \"Auto-merging\" for each file, lists merge strategy used (e.g., 'ort')\n6. Success indicator: \"Merge made by the 'ort' strategy.\" followed by file change summary\n7. Example result: \"40 files changed, 5000 insertions(+), 100 deletions(-)\"\n8. **Modify/delete conflicts:** `-X theirs` doesn't auto-resolve these - requires manual resolution\n   - Example: File deleted in incoming branch but modified in HEAD\n   - Resolution: `git rm {file}` to accept deletion, then `git commit --no-edit` to complete merge\n\n**Git branch rename workflow:**\n1. `git branch -m {old-name} {new-name}` - Rename current branch\n2. `git branch --show-current` - Verify new branch name\n3. Note: Branch rename is local operation, does not affect worktrees or remote\n4. Example: `git branch -m Avanues-Development Avanues-Main` renames the current branch\n\n**Git worktree branch switching workflow:**\n1. `git worktree list` - Lists all worktrees with paths and branches\n2. `git show-ref --verify refs/heads/{branch}` - Verifies branch exists\n3. If worktree missing: `git worktree add ../{repo}-{simplified} {branch}` - Creates new worktree\n4. If worktree exists: Provide `cd` command to switch\n\n**Git worktree reorganization workflow (moving branch from main repo to worktree):**\n1. `git branch --show-current` - Verify current branch on main repo\n2. `git status --short` - Check for uncommitted changes\n3. Commit or stash changes as needed\n4. `git worktree remove {path}` - Remove conflicting worktree if exists\n5. `git checkout {target-branch}` - Switch main repo to target branch\n6. `git worktree add {path} {source-branch}` - Create worktree for original branch\n\n**Git lock file error handling:**\n1. `rm -f .git/index.lock` - Remove specific lock file\n2. If persists: `killall git; sleep 3; find .git -name \"*.lock\" -delete` - Nuclear option\n3. `killall git` more aggressive than `pkill` - terminates all git processes including subprocesses\n4. Sleep 2-3 seconds allows system cleanup before retrying\n\n**Git branch creation from remote:**\n1. `git fetch origin {branch}:{branch}` - Creates local branch from remote\n2. `git checkout {branch}` - Switch to the new branch\n3. Alternative: `git checkout -b {branch} origin/{branch}` - Create and track in one command\n\n**Git push new/renamed branches to remote:**\n1. `git push -u origin {branch-name}` - Push branch and set upstream tracking\n2. Output shows: \"branch '{name}' set up to track 'origin/{name}'\"\n3. GitLab response includes merge request creation URL\n4. Example: `git push -u origin NLU-Development` creates remote branch and tracks it\n\n**Git checkout with merge conflict resolution:**\nWhen switching branches that have diverged:\n1. `rm -f .git/index.lock` (if lock file exists) - Remove stale lock\n2. `git checkout {branch}` - Switch to target branch\n3. If merge conflict occurs: File shows conflict markers (`<<<<<<<`, `=======`, `>>>>>>>`)\n4. Resolve by editing file to keep desired changes from both branches\n5. Remove conflict markers\n6. `git add {conflicted-file}` - Stage resolved file\n7. `git commit` - Complete the merge\n\n**Example workflow executed:**\n```bash\n# First attempt - failed\ngit commit -m \"message\"\n# Error: fatal: Unable to create '.git/index.lock': File exists\n\n# Fix - remove lock file\nrm -f /Volumes/M-Drive/Coding/NewAvanues/.git/index.lock\n\n# Retry - success\ngit commit -m \"message\"\n# [WebAvanue-Development 0e6b3cf9] feat(monorepo): add Cockpit spatial workspace library and Database consolidation\n```\n\nCurrent worktrees output format:\n```\n/Volumes/M-Drive/Coding/NewAvanues          d44c038d [WebAvanue-Development]\n/Volumes/M-Drive/Coding/NewAvanues-VoiceOS  ac531e07 [VoiceOS-Development]\n```\n\n# Errors & Corrections\n_Errors encountered and how they were fixed. What has not? What to avoid? Do not duplicate items from other sections_\n\n**Git worktree confusion:** User stopped worktree removal due to misunderstanding about worktree vs branch persistence. Key learning: Need to clearly explain that `git worktree remove` only removes the working directory checkout, NOT the branch data. The branch remains in git history and can be checked out again. This is a common source of confusion with git worktrees.\n\n**Worktree constraint:** Git won't allow the same branch to be checked out in multiple locations simultaneously (main repo + worktree). To switch main repo to a branch currently in a worktree, you must remove the worktree first, then switch. The branch data is never at risk during this operation.\n\n**Merge conflicts on branch switch:** When switching between development branches that have diverged, expect merge conflicts in shared configuration files like `.claude/CLAUDE.md`. Both branches often modify the same sections independently. Resolution requires manually editing the file to combine desired changes from both branches, then removing conflict markers (`<<<<<<<`, `=======`, `>>>>>>>`). This is normal when branches have been developed in parallel.\n\n**Merge conflicts when merging branches:** Attempting to merge long-diverged development branches (like VoiceOS-Development into Avanues-Main) will produce numerous conflicts. The merge attempt showed 7 conflicts across configuration files, app code, and resources. Two types of conflicts emerged: (1) CONFLICT (add/add) where both branches independently added the same file (e.g., statusline-command.sh, cockpit-mvp files), and (2) CONFLICT (content) where both branches modified the same existing files (VoiceOS source files). This suggests these branches have been developed independently for a significant time. Resolution options: manual conflict resolution (time-consuming), or alternative approaches like selective cherry-picking or creating a fresh merged state.\n\n**Persistent git lock files:** During rapid successive git operations (commits, checkouts, adds), lock file errors may occur multiple times even after removal. This is often due to background processes (like IDE git status checks) or rapid operation sequences. Solution: Remove lock file each time and retry. Lock files are safe to remove when no critical git operations are running. Can verify with `ps aux | grep -i git` to check for running git processes. In this session, lock file errors occurred 6 times total, including during merge abort operations.\n\n**Zombie git processes - requires aggressive termination:** Git lock file errors occurred 7 times in session. Pattern: (1) Simple lock removal works initially, (2) `pkill` partially effective, (3) Zombie processes require `kill -9`, (4) Persistent background processes require `killall`. **Root cause:** Background git processes (status checks, IDE integrations) create lock contention. **Solutions escalate:** `rm -f .git/index.lock` → `pkill -9 git` → `kill -9 {specific PIDs}` → `killall git; sleep 3; find .git -name \"*.lock\" -delete`. **Key learning:** `killall` terminates ALL git processes system-wide including subprocesses that `pkill` misses. Sleep 2-3 seconds after killing allows system cleanup before retrying git operations.\n\n**Statusline content - branch vs worktree:** User asked whether statusline should show worktree name or branch name. Answer: Branch name is more meaningful. Branch = what you're working on (content/feature), Worktree = where you're working (directory location). Showing the branch provides better development context than showing the directory path.\n\n**Avanues-Development as main development branch:** User clarified that \"Avanues-Development is the main branch for the moment for development of all.\" This is important context - Avanues-Development serves as the primary active development branch where all work converges, not just one feature branch among many. This creates a potential tension: we removed Cockpit from Avanues-Development to make it exclusive to Cockpit-Development, but if Avanues is the central integration point, maybe Cockpit should also exist there for integrated development. This question is now pending user decision.\n\n**Build artifacts vs source code:** When removing code from git, leftover build directories may remain as untracked files even after `git rm`. These should be manually deleted with `rm -rf` to fully clean the worktree. In this case, `Common/Cockpit/build/` remained after removing Cockpit source files and needed separate cleanup.\n\n**Evolving requirements during execution:** User interrupted twice during the merge reorganization task (steps 109 and 115) to clarify and refine the branch structure. First interruption specified AVA-Development for \"AVA/NLU Related Code\" (combined). Second interruption separated these: AVA-Development for AVA app only, and separate NLU-Development for NLU library. This shows importance of pausing to get complete requirements before proceeding with complex operations like branch merges. After encountering merge conflicts, it was appropriate to stop and seek clarification rather than making assumptions about the desired structure.\n\n**Critical blocking question pattern:** When facing major architectural decisions (merge-all-branches-first vs create-branches-from-current-state), explicitly present choices rather than proceeding with assumptions. At step 117, posed: \"Should I merge all existing branches into Avanues-Main first? Or should Avanues-Main stay as is and I just create the new development branches?\" Blocks work until answered, but prevents costly rework from wrong assumptions.\n\n**Merge strategy for diverged branches:** Use `git merge -X theirs` (or `-X ours`) to avoid manual conflict resolution when branches have diverged significantly. `-X theirs` accepts all incoming changes, `-X ours` keeps current changes. Particularly useful merging feature branches into master when preserving all features. Step 119-120: Successfully merged 40+ files from VoiceOS-Development with `-X theirs` vs 7 conflicts with default strategy (step 112). Trade-off: Loses selective combination ability, but appropriate for \"all code in one place\" goal (user confirmed step 118). Note: `-X theirs` doesn't handle modify/delete conflicts automatically - these require manual resolution with `git rm` then commit.\n\n**macOS extended attributes on git index:** Git index file may have extended attributes (indicated by `@` in `ls -la .git/index` output on macOS). Can sometimes interfere with git operations. Clear with `xattr -c .git/index` command. How to interpret their output if not obvious?_\n\n**Git merge with automatic conflict resolution:**\n1. `rm -f .git/index.lock` - Remove stale lock file (if needed)\n2. `git merge {branch} -X theirs --no-edit` - Merge accepting all incoming changes\n3. Strategy `-X theirs`: Automatically resolve conflicts by accepting changes from branch being merged\n4. `--no-edit`: Skip commit message editor, use default merge message\n5. Output: Shows \"Auto-merging\" for each file, lists merge strategy used (e.g., 'ort')\n6. Success indicator: \"Merge made by the 'ort' strategy.\" followed by file change summary\n7. Example result: \"40 files changed, 5000 insertions(+), 100 deletions(-)\"\n8. **Modify/delete conflicts:** `-X theirs` doesn't auto-resolve these - requires manual resolution\n   - Example: File deleted in incoming branch but modified in HEAD\n   - Resolution: `git rm {file}` to accept deletion, then `git commit --no-edit` to complete merge\n\n**Git branch rename workflow:**\n1. `git branch -m {old-name} {new-name}` - Rename current branch\n2. `git branch --show-current` - Verify new branch name\n3. Note: Branch rename is local operation, does not affect worktrees or remote\n4. Example: `git branch -m Avanues-Development Avanues-Main` renames the current branch\n\n**Git worktree branch switching workflow:**\n1. `git worktree list` - Lists all worktrees with paths and branches\n2. `git show-ref --verify refs/heads/{branch}` - Verifies branch exists\n3. If worktree missing: `git worktree add ../{repo}-{simplified} {branch}` - Creates new worktree\n4. If worktree exists: Provide `cd` command to switch\n\n**Git worktree reorganization workflow (moving branch from main repo to worktree):**\n1. `git branch --show-current` - Verify current branch on main repo\n2. `git status --short` - Check for uncommitted changes\n3. Commit or stash changes as needed\n4. `git worktree remove {path}` - Remove conflicting worktree if exists\n5. `git checkout {target-branch}` - Switch main repo to target branch\n6. `git worktree add {path} {source-branch}` - Create worktree for original branch\n\n**Git lock file error handling:**\n1. `rm -f .git/index.lock` - Remove specific lock file\n2. If persists: `killall git; sleep 3; find .git -name \"*.lock\" -delete` - Nuclear option\n3. `killall git` more aggressive than `pkill` - terminates all git processes including subprocesses\n4. Sleep 2-3 seconds allows system cleanup before retrying\n\n**Git branch creation from remote:**\n1. `git fetch origin {branch}:{branch}` - Creates local branch from remote\n2. `git checkout {branch}` - Switch to the new branch\n3. Alternative: `git checkout -b {branch} origin/{branch}` - Create and track in one command\n\n**Git push new/renamed branches to remote:**\n1. `git push -u origin {branch-name}` - Push branch and set upstream tracking\n2. Output shows: \"branch '{name}' set up to track 'origin/{name}'\"\n3. GitLab response includes merge request creation URL\n4. Example: `git push -u origin NLU-Development` creates remote branch and tracks it\n\n**Git checkout with merge conflict resolution:**\nWhen switching branches that have diverged:\n1. `rm -f .git/index.lock` (if lock file exists) - Remove stale lock\n2. `git checkout {branch}` - Switch to target branch\n3. If merge conflict occurs: File shows conflict markers (`<<<<<<<`, `=======`, `>>>>>>>`)\n4. Resolve by editing file to keep desired changes from both branches\n5. Remove conflict markers\n6. `git add {conflicted-file}` - Stage resolved file\n7. `git commit` - Complete the merge\n\n**Example workflow executed:**\n```bash\n# First attempt - failed\ngit commit -m \"message\"\n# Error: fatal: Unable to create '.git/index.lock': File exists\n\n# Fix - remove lock file\nrm -f /Volumes/M-Drive/Coding/NewAvanues/.git/index.lock\n\n# Retry - success\ngit commit -m \"message\"\n# [WebAvanue-Development 0e6b3cf9] feat(monorepo): add Cockpit spatial workspace library and Database consolidation\n```\n\nCurrent worktrees output format:\n```\n/Volumes/M-Drive/Coding/NewAvanues          d44c038d [WebAvanue-Development]\n/Volumes/M-Drive/Coding/NewAvanues-VoiceOS  ac531e07 [VoiceOS-Development]\n```\n\n# Errors & Corrections\n_Errors encountered and how they were fixed. What has not? What to avoid? Do not duplicate items from other sections_\n\n**Git worktree confusion:** User stopped worktree removal due to misunderstanding about worktree vs branch persistence. Key learning: Need to clearly explain that `git worktree remove` only removes the working directory checkout, NOT the branch data. The branch remains in git history and can be checked out again. This is a common source of confusion with git worktrees.\n\n**Worktree constraint:** Git won't allow the same branch to be checked out in multiple locations simultaneously (main repo + worktree). To switch main repo to a branch currently in a worktree, you must remove the worktree first, then switch. The branch data is never at risk during this operation.\n\n**Merge conflicts on branch switch:** When switching between development branches that have diverged, expect merge conflicts in shared configuration files like `.claude/CLAUDE.md`. Both branches often modify the same sections independently. Resolution requires manually editing the file to combine desired changes from both branches, then removing conflict markers (`<<<<<<<`, `=======`, `>>>>>>>`). This is normal when branches have been developed in parallel.\n\n**Merge conflicts when merging branches:** Attempting to merge long-diverged development branches (like VoiceOS-Development into Avanues-Main) will produce numerous conflicts. The merge attempt showed 7 conflicts across configuration files, app code, and resources. Two types of conflicts emerged: (1) CONFLICT (add/add) where both branches independently added the same file (e.g., statusline-command.sh, cockpit-mvp files), and (2) CONFLICT (content) where both branches modified the same existing files (VoiceOS source files). This suggests these branches have been developed independently for a significant time. Resolution options: manual conflict resolution (time-consuming), or alternative approaches like selective cherry-picking or creating a fresh merged state.\n\n**Persistent git lock files:** During rapid successive git operations (commits, checkouts, adds), lock file errors may occur multiple times even after removal. This is often due to background processes (like IDE git status checks) or rapid operation sequences. Solution: Remove lock file each time and retry. Lock files are safe to remove when no critical git operations are running. Can verify with `ps aux | grep -i git` to check for running git processes. In this session, lock file errors occurred 6 times total, including during merge abort operations.\n\n**Zombie git processes - requires aggressive termination:** Git lock file errors occurred 7 times in session. Pattern: (1) Simple lock removal works initially, (2) `pkill` partially effective, (3) Zombie processes require `kill -9`, (4) Persistent background processes require `killall`. **Root cause:** Background git processes (status checks, IDE integrations) create lock contention. **Solutions escalate:** `rm -f .git/index.lock` → `pkill -9 git` → `kill -9 {specific PIDs}` → `killall git; sleep 3; find .git -name \"*.lock\" -delete`. **Key learning:** `killall` terminates ALL git processes system-wide including subprocesses that `pkill` misses. Sleep 2-3 seconds after killing allows system cleanup before retrying git operations.\n\n**Statusline content - branch vs worktree:** User asked whether statusline should show worktree name or branch name. Answer: Branch name is more meaningful. Branch = what you're working on (content/feature), Worktree = where you're working (directory location). Showing the branch provides better development context than showing the directory path.\n\n**Avanues-Development as main development branch:** User clarified that \"Avanues-Development is the main branch for the moment for development of all.\" This is important context - Avanues-Development serves as the primary active development branch where all work converges, not just one feature branch among many. This creates a potential tension: we removed Cockpit from Avanues-Development to make it exclusive to Cockpit-Development, but if Avanues is the central integration point, maybe Cockpit should also exist there for integrated development. This question is now pending user decision.\n\n**Build artifacts vs source code:** When removing code from git, leftover build directories may remain as untracked files even after `git rm`. These should be manually deleted with `rm -rf` to fully clean the worktree. In this case, `Common/Cockpit/build/` remained after removing Cockpit source files and needed separate cleanup.\n\n**Evolving requirements during execution:** User interrupted twice during the merge reorganization task (steps 109 and 115) to clarify and refine the branch structure. First interruption specified AVA-Development for \"AVA/NLU Related Code\" (combined). Second interruption separated these: AVA-Development for AVA app only, and separate NLU-Development for NLU library. This shows importance of pausing to get complete requirements before proceeding with complex operations like branch merges. After encountering merge conflicts, it was appropriate to stop and seek clarification rather than making assumptions about the desired structure.\n\n**Critical blocking question pattern:** When facing major architectural decisions (merge-all-branches-first vs create-branches-from-current-state), explicitly present choices rather than proceeding with assumptions. At step 117, posed: \"Should I merge all existing branches into Avanues-Main first? Or should Avanues-Main stay as is and I just create the new development branches?\" Blocks work until answered, but prevents costly rework from wrong assumptions.\n\n**Merge strategy for diverged branches:** Use `git merge -X theirs` (or `-X ours`) to avoid manual conflict resolution when branches have diverged significantly. `-X theirs` accepts all incoming changes, `-X ours` keeps current changes. Particularly useful merging feature branches into master when preserving all features. Step 119-120: Successfully merged 40+ files from VoiceOS-Development with `-X theirs` vs 7 conflicts with default strategy (step 112). Trade-off: Loses selective combination ability, but appropriate for \"all code in one place\" goal (user confirmed step 118). Note: `-X theirs` doesn't handle modify/delete conflicts automatically - these require manual resolution with `git rm` then commit.\n\n**macOS extended attributes on git index:** Git index file may have extended attributes (indicated by `@` in `ls -la .git/index` output on macOS). Can sometimes interfere with git operations. Clear with `xattr -c .git/index` command. However, in step 130, clearing attributes didn't resolve persistent index write error, suggesting issue runs deeper than extended attributes alone.\n\n**Worktree physical vs git content mismatch:** Worktrees may contain physical directories not tracked in their branch's git history. When `git worktree add` creates a worktree, it checks out tracked files for that branch, but may inherit untracked files from main repo state. Use `git ls-tree -r HEAD | grep {path}` to verify what's actually in git before attempting `git rm`. For untracked files, use `rm -rf` directly - `git rm` has no effect on them.\n\n**Monorepo isolation strategy:** (1) **Apps** - isolate to respective branches only (VoiceOS app → VoiceOS-Development only), (2) **Dependencies** - keep shared libraries apps need (Common/Database, ThirdParty, UI, Utils), (3) **Verification** - check with `git ls-tree` what's tracked before removal. User guidance: \"you dont have to remove items if they are to be merged into the app\" - preserve dependencies, remove only misplaced apps.\n\n**Parallel git push efficiency:** Push multiple independent branches in parallel using multiple bash commands in single message. In steps 179-181, pushed 5 branches simultaneously (WebAvanue already synced, other 4 pushed successfully). All completed in single operation vs sequential pushing.
